60
00:03:44,391 --> 00:03:47,851
<i>Retrouvez-nous chaque semaine...</i>

61
00:03:48,961 --> 00:03:52,346
<i>pour découvrir les énigmes de</i>

62
00:03:52,471 --> 00:03:55,109
<i>Saison 2 Épisode 17
-Olivia. In The Lab. With The Revolver.-</i>

63
00:03:55,234 --> 00:03:56,443
<i>Bon épisode...</i>

64
00:04:20,568 --> 00:04:21,568
Hello?

65
00:04:21,900 --> 00:04:23,053
Is that you, Dunham?

66
00:04:23,221 --> 00:04:26,473
I thought you'd quit bowling,
took up another sport.

67
00:04:27,061 --> 00:04:28,517
It's been a while.

68
00:04:29,348 --> 00:04:31,395
I see you're still not sleeping.

69
00:04:32,006 --> 00:04:33,674
Not so much. No.

70
00:04:34,459 --> 00:04:35,774
Can you pass me a nut?

71
00:04:37,129 --> 00:04:38,177
Yeah, sure.

72
00:04:38,618 --> 00:04:39,778
Which one?

73
00:04:39,946 --> 00:04:41,405
Dealer's choice.

74
00:04:47,512 --> 00:04:48,245
Perfect.

75
00:04:52,599 --> 00:04:54,084
What's on your mind?

76
00:04:57,631 --> 00:04:58,631
Well...

77
00:05:01,343 --> 00:05:05,313
After my car accident,
you said that...

78
00:05:06,936 --> 00:05:09,636
I would experience things.

79
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:12,480
I have.

80
00:05:17,751 --> 00:05:18,941
You want a beer?

81
00:05:19,475 --> 00:05:21,421
It's 6:30 in the morning.

82
00:05:21,546 --> 00:05:23,362
When you've been up all night,

83
00:05:23,487 --> 00:05:25,737
time is just a matter of semantics.

84
00:05:27,198 --> 00:05:28,136
Thanks.

85
00:05:28,472 --> 00:05:31,322
So I suppose you're here
to find out what happens next.

86
00:05:32,111 --> 00:05:33,261
Suppose I am.

87
00:05:34,627 --> 00:05:35,927
I can't tell ya.

88
00:05:36,052 --> 00:05:39,296
You have officially gone
beyond my field of expertise.

89
00:05:39,789 --> 00:05:42,866
But I believe I can tell you
why you're not sleeping.

90
00:05:43,241 --> 00:05:45,427
And it has nothing to do
with your accident.

91
00:05:48,638 --> 00:05:49,788
You're a cop.

92
00:05:50,942 --> 00:05:54,406
You must make a dozen decisions a day,
many of them life and death.

93
00:05:54,531 --> 00:05:56,513
One of them you're not happy about.

94
00:05:57,969 --> 00:06:00,118
You think you did the wrong thing.

95
00:06:01,477 --> 00:06:03,067
I'm right, aren't I?

96
00:06:09,142 --> 00:06:10,646
But it wasn't the job.

97
00:06:12,369 --> 00:06:13,546
Not exactly.

98
00:06:16,376 --> 00:06:18,176
I agreed to keep a secret.

99
00:06:18,883 --> 00:06:19,883
A secret.

100
00:06:30,974 --> 00:06:31,985
I'm on my way.

101
00:06:33,622 --> 00:06:35,394
It's a good thing
you didn't take the beer.

102
00:06:36,784 --> 00:06:38,005
I'll see you later.

103
00:06:41,917 --> 00:06:43,467
You're a good person.

104
00:06:44,376 --> 00:06:46,071
One of the few I know.

105
00:06:47,707 --> 00:06:50,712
If you agreed to keep this secret,
I'm sure you had a good reason.

106
00:07:00,561 --> 00:07:02,754
Killington?
As in skiing?

107
00:07:02,879 --> 00:07:04,649
They just had a fresh snowfall.

108
00:07:05,212 --> 00:07:07,227
I had no idea you were a skier.

109
00:07:07,352 --> 00:07:08,703
Oh, yes.

110
00:07:08,828 --> 00:07:10,679
I was quite a hotdogger.

111
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:14,153
I remember
there was this secret trail.

112
00:07:14,884 --> 00:07:16,444
They called it "the backside,"

113
00:07:16,569 --> 00:07:18,392
but not for the reason
you would think.

114
00:07:18,517 --> 00:07:20,086
It was a nude ski run.

115
00:07:20,211 --> 00:07:23,915
By the time you got down to the bottom,
your testicles would be in your mouth.

116
00:07:25,005 --> 00:07:27,996
I'm sure Agent Dunham
is very thankful for that image.

117
00:07:28,121 --> 00:07:30,165
Walter's advocating
a father-son trip.

118
00:07:30,290 --> 00:07:33,083
And I'm sure Agent Dunham
is not interested in that.

119
00:07:35,396 --> 00:07:38,914
I understand that Agent Broyles
has a body for us to look at.

120
00:07:39,164 --> 00:07:41,014
Her name is Miranda Greene.

121
00:07:41,548 --> 00:07:43,494
30 years old, unmarried.
She was an attorney.

122
00:07:43,619 --> 00:07:44,838
Lived here in providence.

123
00:07:45,006 --> 00:07:48,212
EMTs responded to a 911 call
phoned in by a good samaritan.

124
00:07:48,629 --> 00:07:50,600
She was dead
by the time they arrived.

125
00:07:52,658 --> 00:07:53,658
Doctor.

126
00:07:54,426 --> 00:07:55,891
This is Agent Olivia Dunham.

127
00:07:56,059 --> 00:07:59,021
- This is Peter Bishop and Dr...
- Walter Bishop.

128
00:08:00,676 --> 00:08:04,316
John Potash. I took your advanced
biochem seminar, Dr. Bishop.

129
00:08:05,554 --> 00:08:06,975
I apologize.

130
00:08:07,763 --> 00:08:10,602
I remember I was
a bit of a slave driver.

131
00:08:10,977 --> 00:08:11,740
You were.

132
00:08:11,908 --> 00:08:13,408
But also inspiring.

133
00:08:14,294 --> 00:08:17,121
The truth is
I was considering changing majors,

134
00:08:17,246 --> 00:08:20,293
but you encouraged me to stick
with it and become a doctor.

135
00:08:21,226 --> 00:08:23,375
I never thought I'd get
a chance to thank you.

136
00:08:23,500 --> 00:08:25,754
Your father is a great man.

137
00:08:26,765 --> 00:08:27,765
Doctor,

138
00:08:28,124 --> 00:08:29,883
which one is Miranda Greene?

139
00:08:31,419 --> 00:08:32,421
Right this way.

140
00:08:33,388 --> 00:08:36,014
I'm sorry.
This might be a bit unpleasant.

141
00:08:38,539 --> 00:08:40,102
Epidermal blistering.

142
00:08:41,103 --> 00:08:42,403
Tissue necrosis.

143
00:08:42,856 --> 00:08:45,050
Symptomatic of cytotoxins.

144
00:08:46,724 --> 00:08:48,944
Could you get a sample
of this pus please, Peter?

145
00:08:49,112 --> 00:08:50,412
I always get the good jobs.

146
00:08:50,537 --> 00:08:52,567
According to her coworkers,
when she left for lunch,

147
00:08:52,692 --> 00:08:54,950
she was perfectly fine.
Any signs of illness.

148
00:08:55,259 --> 00:08:57,614
That was about two hours
before the 911 call.

149
00:08:58,455 --> 00:09:00,934
I was considering
that these are contact burns

150
00:09:01,059 --> 00:09:02,880
from some sort
of synthetic chemical.

151
00:09:03,258 --> 00:09:04,793
No, these aren't chemical burns.

152
00:09:07,360 --> 00:09:10,132
They look more like
malignant tumors.

153
00:09:10,713 --> 00:09:11,466
Cancer?

154
00:09:11,759 --> 00:09:13,340
Sarcomas, to be exact.

155
00:09:13,767 --> 00:09:15,679
But that kind of cancer

156
00:09:15,847 --> 00:09:17,885
presents beneath the skin,
not on the surface.

157
00:09:18,010 --> 00:09:18,974
Normally, yes.

158
00:09:20,466 --> 00:09:23,070
- Do you have a black light?
- Yeah. Somewhere.

159
00:09:24,519 --> 00:09:26,476
- What is it, Walter?
- I'm not sure.

160
00:09:26,601 --> 00:09:29,010
Cancers always start

161
00:09:29,135 --> 00:09:31,154
with a specific point of origin,

162
00:09:31,279 --> 00:09:33,578
and they spread from there, so...

163
00:09:35,285 --> 00:09:36,219
Here you go.

164
00:09:36,701 --> 00:09:38,375
Agent Broyles, lights, please.

165
00:09:40,481 --> 00:09:43,947
The cells near the point
of origin of the cancer

166
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:46,291
should show more progression,

167
00:09:46,595 --> 00:09:49,546
and hence refract a different color.

168
00:09:53,075 --> 00:09:55,339
Like that.

169
00:09:58,098 --> 00:10:00,265
- It looks like...
- Fingers.

170
00:10:01,884 --> 00:10:04,425
Indeed.
Right hand, I'd say.

171
00:10:04,682 --> 00:10:05,973
Which indicates

172
00:10:06,098 --> 00:10:09,877
not only what killed this woman,

173
00:10:11,108 --> 00:10:12,236
but also who.

174
00:10:13,630 --> 00:10:16,169
Of course, somehow
we'll need to retrieve a print.

175
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:19,252
What you're suggesting
is impossible...

176
00:10:19,958 --> 00:10:22,983
That someone touched this woman
and gave her cancer?

177
00:10:23,108 --> 00:10:26,041
It seems you've forgotten
my very first lesson, Doctor.

178
00:10:26,539 --> 00:10:29,207
When you open your mind
to the impossible,

179
00:10:29,980 --> 00:10:31,757
sometimes you find the truth.

180
00:10:39,814 --> 00:10:41,480
28 degrees fahrenheit,

181
00:10:41,605 --> 00:10:43,392
and they're predicting snow
next week.

182
00:10:43,517 --> 00:10:45,202
Hardly ideal beach weather.

183
00:10:45,327 --> 00:10:47,170
Why are you going to Atlantic City?

184
00:10:47,524 --> 00:10:49,257
I was thinking
of taking Peter there.

185
00:10:50,246 --> 00:10:53,060
Used to love
saltwater taffy as a child.

186
00:10:53,858 --> 00:10:55,627
So what are we looking for?

187
00:10:55,919 --> 00:10:58,240
Why are we cutting off
this poor woman's arm?

188
00:10:58,562 --> 00:11:00,675
The handprint shows

189
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:04,025
an extraordinary level
of cellular detail.

190
00:11:06,304 --> 00:11:07,454
I'm hoping...

191
00:11:11,719 --> 00:11:14,262
Hoping to be able
to remove the tumor, and...

192
00:11:14,761 --> 00:11:16,222
bake the skin, and...

193
00:11:16,716 --> 00:11:19,355
Hopefully identify a fingerprint.

194
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:22,389
And I'll need
two hot baths and an oven.

195
00:11:22,733 --> 00:11:25,577
You really think someone may have
touched her and given her cancer?

196
00:11:25,702 --> 00:11:28,541
Terrifying possibility,
but a possibility nonetheless.

197
00:11:32,135 --> 00:11:33,485
We need glycerin,

198
00:11:33,907 --> 00:11:35,907
corn starch and food coloring.

199
00:11:36,195 --> 00:11:37,279
Food coloring?

200
00:11:37,447 --> 00:11:40,498
Not for her, but since we're baking,
we may as well make some taffy.

201
00:11:43,419 --> 00:11:45,462
I've worked with Miranda
for about seven years.

202
00:11:45,587 --> 00:11:47,399
She was fairly private,
but if she was sick,

203
00:11:47,524 --> 00:11:48,845
I think someone would know.

204
00:11:48,970 --> 00:11:51,996
So what sort of cases did Miranda
usually work on, Mr. Messing?

205
00:11:52,317 --> 00:11:54,796
Mostly toxic tort litigation.
Class action stuff.

206
00:11:55,151 --> 00:11:56,793
Asbestos, lead poisoning.

207
00:11:57,185 --> 00:12:00,346
She had a real thing about protecting
those who couldn't protect themselves.

208
00:12:01,891 --> 00:12:03,765
And is this what she was working on?

209
00:12:06,326 --> 00:12:09,101
She was prepping a case
against Intrepus Pharmaceuticals.

210
00:12:09,838 --> 00:12:11,772
Trial was supposed
to start next week.

211
00:12:13,100 --> 00:12:15,025
How much money
was at stake in the trial?

212
00:12:15,619 --> 00:12:16,860
North eight figures.

213
00:12:21,353 --> 00:12:24,505
Wait, are you suggesting
that someone did this to her?

214
00:12:24,894 --> 00:12:27,353
I thought she contracted
some kind of crazy disease.

215
00:12:27,478 --> 00:12:29,414
we're not sure,
but we like to be thorough.

216
00:12:29,833 --> 00:12:32,292
Can we take her files
on the Intrepus case?

217
00:12:32,936 --> 00:12:34,218
Of course. Yeah.

218
00:12:34,671 --> 00:12:36,605
Miss Greene had meetings
scheduled for yesterday.

219
00:12:36,730 --> 00:12:38,131
Do you recognize those names?

220
00:12:39,534 --> 00:12:41,134
First two are deposition prep.

221
00:12:42,191 --> 00:12:43,720
I don't recognize the third one.

222
00:12:45,828 --> 00:12:46,892
Neil Wilson.

223
00:12:47,573 --> 00:12:49,983
She was supposed to meet him
about an hour before she died.

224
00:12:52,343 --> 00:12:54,898
Do you really think that Intrepus
Pharmaceutical killed this woman?

225
00:12:55,531 --> 00:12:57,234
Maybe. You don't?

226
00:12:57,359 --> 00:13:00,039
I've never heard of a drug that can cause
what happened to Miranda Greene.

227
00:13:00,164 --> 00:13:02,812
It seems like an awful lot of trouble
to go through to kill somebody.

228
00:13:02,937 --> 00:13:04,238
Why not just hire a hit man?

229
00:13:04,363 --> 00:13:06,108
A hitman would draw
too much attention.

230
00:13:06,233 --> 00:13:06,963
Really?

231
00:13:07,167 --> 00:13:09,204
And spontaneous
fatal tumor-growth wouldn't?

232
00:13:10,104 --> 00:13:11,957
I suppose you have a point.

233
00:13:20,723 --> 00:13:23,370
You want to come on inside, we can
noodle on it? Maybe order a pizza?

234
00:13:24,258 --> 00:13:25,285
Thanks, but, no.

235
00:13:25,410 --> 00:13:28,028
I didn't get much sleep last night,
so I should probably head home.

236
00:13:28,153 --> 00:13:29,960
Anyway, I'm not
really hungry, but...

237
00:13:30,085 --> 00:13:31,477
- All right.
- Thank you.

238
00:13:57,029 --> 00:13:58,392
Agent Dunham.

239
00:13:59,122 --> 00:14:00,410
You're up early.

240
00:14:02,006 --> 00:14:03,567
I ran Neil Wilson's number.

241
00:14:03,692 --> 00:14:06,428
It's a disposable cell phone,
and it was deactivated yesterday.

242
00:14:06,596 --> 00:14:07,917
It's a pretty common name.

243
00:14:08,042 --> 00:14:10,891
I checked, and there's more than
50 Neil Wilsons in the tri-state area.

244
00:14:11,371 --> 00:14:13,263
Do you want me to start
running them down?

245
00:14:13,820 --> 00:14:16,488
I'm pretty sure he gave her
a fake name anyway, so...

246
00:14:18,872 --> 00:14:20,609
Could you give
Walter and I a minute?

247
00:14:21,452 --> 00:14:22,270
Sure.

248
00:14:24,450 --> 00:14:25,862
Don't mix up the spoons.

249
00:14:30,565 --> 00:14:31,745
Help me stir.

250
00:14:38,947 --> 00:14:41,671
Walter, I have to tell him.
I got to tell Peter the truth.

251
00:14:43,734 --> 00:14:47,552
- But that's not what we discussed.
- I know, and I'm sorry.

252
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:50,285
But he deserves to know the truth
about who he is.

253
00:14:51,099 --> 00:14:52,849
No, you don't understand.

254
00:14:53,054 --> 00:14:54,802
Things have never been
better between us.

255
00:14:54,927 --> 00:14:57,316
I can't lose him again. I can't.

256
00:14:57,441 --> 00:14:58,491
You won't.

257
00:14:58,776 --> 00:15:00,148
Once he knows the whole story.

